 | url-status = dead
 }}</ref>
On 9 June 2021, Hull City announced that Jones had signed a new two-year contract, with the club having the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite news
 | url = https://www.hullcitytigers.com/news/2021/june/alfie-jones-signs-new-contract/
 | title = Alfie Jones Signs New Contract
 | date = 9 June 2021
 | publisher = Hull City A.F.C.
 | accessdate = 9 June 2021}}</ref>

On 23 April 2022, Jones scored his first goal for the Tigers, netting the second of three goals in Hull's 3–0 home win over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref>{{cite news
 | url = https://www.wearehullcity.co.uk/news/2022/april2/hull-city-3-0-reading-match-report/
 | title = Hull City 3–0 Reading: Match Report
 | date =23 April 2022
 | publisher = Hull City A.F.C.
 | accessdate = 9 August 2024}}</ref> The following season, on 2 May 2023, Jones was decorated with Hull's Player of the Year award, as decided by head coach, [[Liam Rosenior]].<ref name = "POTS">{{cite news
 | url = https://www.wearehullcity.co.uk/news/2023/may/slater-wins-duo-of-awards/
 | title = Slater wins duo of awards
 | date = 2 May 2023
 | publisher = Hull City A.F.C.
 | accessdate = 6 May 2023}}</ref> On 17 May 2023, Jones signed a new three-year deal with the club.<ref name="New Hull deal">{{cite news
 | url = https://www.wearehullcity.co.uk/news/2023/may/jones-pens-new-long-term-deal/
 | title = Jones pens new long-term deal
 | date =17 May 2023
 | publisher = Hull City A.F.C.
 | accessdate = 17 May 2023}}</ref>

In July 2025, Jones joined [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite news |date=25 July 2025 |title=Alfie Jones: Middlesbrough sign defender from Hull City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c7vrvy99l7do |access-date=25 July 2025 |website=BBC Sport }}</ref>

==International career==
Jones is eligible to represent Canada through his grandmother, who was born in [[Hillcrest, Alberta]].<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |last=Molinaro |first=John |date=2025-11-12 |title='In my bloodline': Defender Alfie Jones embracing move to Canadian men's national team |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/article/in-my-bloodline-defender-alfie-jones-embracing-move-to-canadian-mens-national-team/ |access-date=2025-11-12 |website=Sportsnet.ca |language=en}}</ref> His eligibility became known after discussions with teammate [[Liam Millar]] during their time together at Hull City.<ref name="auto"/>

He was approached to play for the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]] in October 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6713471/2025/10/13/what-im-hearing-inside-canadas-roster-battles-as-world-cup-approaches/|title=What I’m hearing: Inside Canada’s roster battles as World Cup approaches|first=Joshua|last=Kloke|date=13 October 2025|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In November 2025, he was named in the squad ahead of a pair of friendlies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onesoccer.ca/a/jesse-marsch-makes-short-and-long-term-bets-with-can-mnt-dual-nationals-goodman-jones-and-flores|title=1-ON-1 🎙️ + SQUAD ANALYSIS: Jesse Marsch calls up CanMNT dual-nationals Alfie Jones, Owen Goodman & Marcelo Flores|date=November 6, 2025|first=Alexandre|last=Gangué-Ruzic|work=[[OneSoccer]]}}</ref> Administrative delays on his citizenship meant he was not eligible for the first match against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]], but these were resolved by the time of the second match against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], in which he started.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Connor Clarke |first1=Charlie |title=Alfie Jones officially eligible for CanMNT, will start vs. Venezuela |url=https://www.onesoccer.ca/a/alfie-jones-officially-eligible-for-can-mnt-will-start-vs-venezuela |access-date=19 November 2025 |publisher=OneSoccer}}</ref> Jones played the full 90 minutes in Canada's 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tierney |first1=Mitchell |title=ANALYSIS + HIGHLIGHTS: CanMNT end 2025 on a winning note in fiesty 2-0 victory over Venezuela |url=https://www.onesoccer.ca/a/analysis-highlights-can-mnt-end-2025-on-a-winning-note-in-fiesty-2-0-victory-over-venezuela |access-date=19 November 2025 |publisher=OneSoccer}}</ref>

In May 2026, Jones was called-up to Canada's squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northerntribune.ca/world-cup-2026-canada-squad/|first=John|last=Jacques|date=May 29, 2026|title=Here’s The Canada World Cup Roster|work=Northern Tribune}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Having been used mostly as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] prior to his arrival at [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], Jones spent most of his time with the [[EFL League One|League One]] club playing as a [[midfielder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/sport/a-credit-to-the-saints-210897/|title=Southampton loanee Alfie Jones revelling in midfield position at Gillingham|website=kentonline.co.uk|date=23 August 2019|accessdate=4 September 2020}}</ref> However, since moving to [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], he has returned to being a defender.<ref name="New Hull deal"/> In 2023, then Hull coach [[Liam Rosenior]] highlighted Jones' interceptions, blocks, and ball-playing abilities as being amongst his best attributes.<ref name="New Hull deal"/>

